    <item>
      <title>Django App from Scratch Using Docker with Debian Base Image</title>
      <link>/posts/django-app-from-scratch/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 24 May 2022 22:30:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>/posts/django-app-from-scratch/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Pull a Fresh Debian Image&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;pull-a-fresh-debian-image&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#pull-a-fresh-debian-image&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Create a docker container from a Debian image, the following command can be used to pull a debain 11-slim image and create a container of it, also enter into the container in a interactive environment &lt;code&gt;-it&lt;/code&gt; mode.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight-wrapper&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;docker run -v $(pwd):/var/www --rm -it -p 8001:80 debian:11-slim&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Create a Django App from Shell script&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;create-a-django-app-from-shell-script&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#create-a-django-app-from-shell-script&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Now, since we are inside a Debian container, we can enter a few commands, you can refer to the Mark Gibney&amp;rsquo;s &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/no-gravity/web_app_from_scratch&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;GitHub repository&lt;/a&gt; for the script.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Dockerize a Django project</title>
      <link>/posts/dockerize-django-prj/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 02 Mar 2022 19:12:51 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>/posts/dockerize-django-prj/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Dockerize a Django project&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;dockerize-a-django-project&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#dockerize-a-django-project&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;We can run our Django projects in a Docker Container by creating a Docker image for our project. It is really easy and intuitive to create a Dockerfile for any given application as it really is a matter of writing commands in a file and basically running it is a isolated environment. To create a Docker image, we first need a Dockerfile. A Dockerfile is simply a Blueprint to create a image in Docker. In this file we specify the instructions/commands/environment variables to create a image for our app to run.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Docker Port Forwarding</title>
      <link>/posts/docker-port-forward/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 01 Mar 2022 16:44:59 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>/posts/docker-port-forward/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Docker Port Forwarding&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;docker-port-forwarding&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#docker-port-forwarding&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Port forwarding is a process to redirect the communication of one address to other.&lt;br&gt;&#xA;It is also known as Port Binding.&lt;br&gt;&#xA;We can use &lt;code&gt;-p&lt;/code&gt; command to use port forwarding in our local Docker environment.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight-wrapper&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;docker run -p 8000:8000 django-app&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The first port number is the local machine port and followed by a &lt;code&gt;:&lt;/code&gt; is the container port number.&lt;br&gt;&#xA;SO, the request from the container port are forwarded to the local/outside world in the docker environment.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
